</summary><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;The goal of Least Squares is to find a mathematical model, or an approximate model, of some relationship, given some observed data or measurements or sampled signals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;object data="/data/wop50-09.svg" style="width: 600px; height: 450px;" type="image/svg+xml"&gt;
Least Squares model of World Oil Production data from 1950 to 2009&lt;/object&gt;
&lt;div class="section" id="formulation"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Formulation&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Suppose we have an n-vector &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt;, and a scalar &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(y\)&lt;/span&gt;, and we believe that they are related, perhaps approximately, by some function &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(f : \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow  \mathbb{R}\)&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;
\begin{equation*}
y \approx f(x)
\end{equation*}
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The vector &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt; might represent a set of n feature values, and is called the &lt;em&gt;feature vector&lt;/em&gt; or the vector of &lt;em&gt;independent variables&lt;/em&gt;, depending on the context. The scalar &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(y\)&lt;/span&gt; represents some &lt;em&gt;outcome&lt;/em&gt; (also called &lt;em&gt;response variable&lt;/em&gt;) that we are interested in.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
